I&#x27;m trying to explain this in as much brevity as I can, but this will be a long post.<p>> What do you mean by &quot;at runtime&quot;? The only language that I&#x27;m familiar with that really lets you define them at runtime is Lisp.<p>Lisp is not the only language that allows this. This is why I mentioned JavaScript at the end of my last comment. In general, it would be easy for a scripting language to support this feature. What&#x27;s more interesting is that some compiled languages do as well. For example, Chicken Scheme. Scheme being a form of Lisp supports first-class functions, and Chicken Scheme being a compiled form of Scheme does as well.<p>An example from JavaScript:<p><pre><code>  function ValueAlerter(x)
  {
    return function () {
      window.alert(x);
    }
  }</code></pre>
Any time this function is called (ValueAlerter), a new unnamed function is created that references the closure of ValueAlerter.<p>It&#x27;s possible to write the same thing with a named function.<p><pre><code>  function ValueAlerter(x)
  {
    function result() {
      window.alert(x);
    }
    return result;
  }</code></pre>
Note that this is, using prototypes, generally how OOP is implemented in JavaScript.<p>> > Lambdas are essentially syntactic sugar.<p>> Do you mean that lambdas are essentially syntactic sugar for creating functions at runtime? Because C++ has lambdas, and if you mean &quot;lambdas = creating functions at runtime = functions as first-class values&quot;, well, C++ has lambdas...<p>> Could you clarify? I&#x27;m sorry, but I&#x27;m having trouble seeing what distinctions you&#x27;re trying to draw.<p>When a language feature is called syntactic sugar, it means that it makes certain ideas easier to express, but it doesn&#x27;t create new functionality. An example in C++ is the -> operator. The alternative to writing a->b is (*a).b which is more cumbersome.<p>So no, lambdas do not allow you to create &quot;functions&quot; at runtime (when speaking of our complete definition of a first-class function). I would assume that a C compiler is able to isolate the code in a lambda into its own function, so it is equivalent to writing a separate function, depending on how it is referenced. The `auto&#x27; type also facilitates this because newer C++ features involve certain types which cannot be used by the programmer.<p>So you can think of C++ lambdas as a sort of macro for writing code locally. It&#x27;s similar to using<p><pre><code>  a = p ? x : y;
</code></pre>
instead of<p><pre><code>  if (p) a = x; else a = y;
</code></pre>
in that it is a language feature that allows for the programmer to type less for the same result.<p>--<p>For a more illustrated example, think of a basic sequence of function calls. Function A calls B, and B calls C. The callstack in a C++ program for this sequence would look like this:<p><pre><code>  A()
    B()
      C()
</code></pre>
The computer&#x27;s stack looks like this when it is executed:<p><pre><code>  Top of the Stack
  ----
  A&#x27;s local variables.
  ----
  B&#x27;s local variables.
  ----
  C&#x27;s local variables.
  ----
  Bottom of the Stack
</code></pre>
Now, it&#x27;s possible for C() to create a function and store that somewhere. In a C++ lambda, with a captured local variable, this dynamic function would have a reference to one of C()&#x27;s local variables. In a JavaScript or Lisp program, this dynamic function would also have access to one of C()&#x27;s locals. This is fine if the dynamic function is called when C() is still in scope.<p>If, however, this is stored in a result that is accessible from A() and it is executed after B() is out of scope, and this function references a local value from C(), then the reference would look something like this:<p><pre><code>  Top of the Stack
  ----
  A&#x27;s local variables.
  ----
  Bottom of the Stack
  ----
  Garbage
  ----
  Garbage (Reference to C() variable)
  ----
</code></pre>
So basically, native C or C++ functions cannot be first-class with this model of computation, while it&#x27;s trivial for Lisp and Scheme. Now it is possible to use this sort of paradigm with a number of templates, libraries, strategies, added language features, but nothing that approaches native first-class functions.<p>Making a sincere implementation of this would be more daunting than creating a new language.
